{"type":"message","id":"dcd9ed87","parentId":"5541fcb3","timestamp":"2026-05-07T05:01:10.223Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me compile the data:\n\n**Crypto (from CoinGecko):**\n- BTC: $80,957 (~VND 2,130,096,680) | 24h: -0.37%\n- ETH: $2,326.66 (~VND 61,217,903) | 24h: -1.60%\n- SOL: $88.3 (~VND 2,323,226) | 24h: +1.72%\n- TON: $2.82 (~VND 74,306) | 24h: +29.10%\n\n**Gold:**\n- World XAU: from Investing.com VN snippet shows 4,702.51 - let me use that\n- SJC VN: From baonghean.vn snippet - 163 triệu đồng/lượng mua vào, VOV says 164.5 - 167.5 triệu. Let me use the more recent one from VOV: 164.5 – 167.5 triệu\n\n**Oil:**\n- WTI: fortune.com says $106.52/barrel (May 6), oilpriceapi.com says $95.68, fxleaders says $106. The fortune.com article is \"17 giờ trước\" and says $106.52 for Brent, and the Forbes article from May 6 says WTI opened at $102.67. Let me use the most recent from fortune - wait, let me re-read. Fortune says \"At 8:30 a.m. Eastern Time today, the price of oil sits at $106.52 per barrel, using Brent as the benchmark\" - so that's Brent. Forbes says WTI opened at $102.67 on May 6. Brent: tradingeconomics says \"Brent rose to 101.96 USD/Bbl on May 7\" so I'll use 101.96.\n\n\n- WTI: I'll use around $102-103 based on the Forbes data since the fortune article was specifically about Brent. Looking more carefully at the fortune article - it says $106.52 using Brent as the benchmark, so that's actually Brent. For WTI on May 6, Forbes says $102.67, and on May 7 tradingeconomics doesn't show WTI. For Brent, tradingeconomics shows 101.96 on May 7.\n\n- Oil prices are conflicting across sources - fortune shows $106.52 for Brent but that's from their May 6 article, while tradingeconomics shows 101.96 for May 7. I'll go with tradingeconomics as the more current data point, using $102 for WTI and $101.96 for Brent based on the latest available figures.\n\n- Looking at Vietnamese sources for gold and fuel prices, SJC is